ValueMeaning.preferredName: Percent of Nucleotide Markers Exhibiting Instability
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The relative measurement (percentage) of nucleotide repeat markers exhibiting instability to all nucleotide repeat markers tested in a biological specimen.

Concepts.longName: Number of Nucleotide Markers Exhibiting Instability
Concepts.definition: The total number of nucleotide repeat markers tested that exhibit instability in a biological specimen.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The state or condition of a subject's microsatellite sequences with respect to the inability of their mismatch repair (MMR) proteins to fix a DNA replication error.

Concepts.definition: The state or condition of a subject's microsatellite sequences with respect to the inability of their mismatch repair (MMR) proteins to fix a DNA replication error.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Analysis that looks for differences in the lengths of microsatellite repeats between alleles. Polymorphic microsatellites are present in the genome every few thousand base pairs and can function as molecular markers.

Concepts.definition: Analysis that looks for differences in the lengths of microsatellite repeats between alleles. Polymorphic microsatellites are present in the genome every few thousand base pairs and can function as molecular markers.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An assessment of the variability in length of an individual's microsatellite sequences; microsatellite length instability may be due to mismatch repair protein mutation.

Concepts.definition: An assessment of the variability in length of an individual's microsatellite sequences; microsatellite length instability may be due to mismatch repair protein mutation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An act or process of elucidation, explication, or explanation of the meaning of an event or thing.

Concepts.definition: An act or process of elucidation, explication, or explanation of the meaning of an event or thing.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The identification of genetic variation in a biological sample.

Concepts.definition: The identification of genetic variation in a biological sample.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The determination of the DNA sequence of an individual.

Concepts.definition: The determination of the DNA sequence of an individual.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The determination of the level of gene transcription in a biological specimen. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: The determination of the level of gene transcription in a biological specimen. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An indication of the magnitude difference between two values specified as the number of multiples of the first value to the second value (e.g., from 10 to 20 is a 2-fold increase, from 10 to 50 is a five-fold increase).

Concepts.definition: An indication of the magnitude difference between two values specified as the number of multiples of the first value to the second value (e.g., from 10 to 20 is a 2-fold increase, from 10 to 50 is a five-fold increase).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The number of molecules of a particular type on or in a cell or part of a cell. Usually applied to specific genes or to plasmids within a bacterium.

Concepts.definition: The number of molecules of a particular type on or in a cell or part of a cell. Usually applied to specific genes or to plasmids within a bacterium.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Techniques for analysis of chromosomal and subchromosomal properties and structures, such as those to diagnose, classify, screen for, or manage genetic diseases and abnormalities.

Concepts.definition: Techniques for analysis of chromosomal and subchromosomal properties and structures, such as those to diagnose, classify, screen for, or manage genetic diseases and abnormalities.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The number of base pairs present in an RNA or DNA sequence, which is the product of an amplification process.

Concepts.definition: The number of base pairs present in an RNA or DNA sequence, which is the product of an amplification process.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A subgroup of alleles of a polymorphic gene that may form clusters (e.g., phylogenetic) based on high sequence similarity, which may include either a shared single nucleotide polymorphism or a shared set of polymorphic sites.

Concepts.definition: A subgroup of alleles of a polymorphic gene that may form clusters (e.g., phylogenetic) based on high sequence similarity, which may include either a shared single nucleotide polymorphism or a shared set of polymorphic sites.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Mutually exclusive alternative forms of the same gene occupying the same locus on homologous chromosomes, differing in nucleotide sequence and governing the same biochemical and developmental process.

Concepts.definition: Mutually exclusive alternative forms of the same gene occupying the same locus on homologous chromosomes, differing in nucleotide sequence and governing the same biochemical and developmental process.
